when anger arises think of the consequences



Here are hundreds of quotes attributed to Confucius:

### On Wisdom and Knowledge:
1. "Real knowledge is to know the extent of one's ignorance."
2. "The man who asks a question is a fool for a minute, the man who does not ask is a fool for life."
3. "Ignorance is the night of the mind, but a night without moon and star."
4. "By three methods we may learn wisdom: First, by reflection, which is noblest; Second, by imitation, which is easiest; and third by experience, which is the bitterest."
5. "He who learns but does not think, is lost! He who thinks but does not learn is in great danger."
6. "Knowledge without practice is useless. Practice without knowledge is dangerous."
7. "To see what is right and not do it is the want of courage."
8. "The cautious seldom err."
9. "Learning without thought is labor lost; thought without learning is perilous."
10. "He who knows all the answers has not been asked all the questions."
11. "Wisdom, compassion, and courage are the three universally recognized moral qualities of men."
12. "When we see men of a contrary character, we should turn inwards and examine ourselves."
13. "The man of wisdom is never of two minds; the man of benevolence never worries; the man of courage is never afraid."
14. "To know what you know and what you do not know, that is true knowledge."
15. "The essence of knowledge is, having it, to apply it; not having it, to confess your ignorance."
16. "He who learns but does not think, is lost! He who thinks but does not learn is in great danger."
17. "The superior man is modest in his speech, but exceeds in his actions."
18. "A man who has committed a mistake and doesn't correct it is committing another mistake."
19. "He who speaks without modesty will find it difficult to make his words good."
20. "When we see men of a contrary character, we should turn inwards and examine ourselves."

### On Virtue and Morality:
21. "The superior man acts before he speaks, and afterwards speaks according to his actions."
22. "What you do not want done to yourself, do not do to others."
23. "Virtue is not left to stand alone. He who practices it will have neighbors."
24. "To see the right and not do it is the want of courage."
25. "It is not possible for one to teach others who cannot teach his own family."
26. "The strength of a nation derives from the integrity of the home."
27. "The superior man is modest in his speech but exceeds in his actions."
28. "The superior man is slow in his words and earnest in his conduct."
29. "The superior man understands what is right; the inferior man understands what will sell."
30. "The superior man is distressed by his want of ability, not by men's ignorance of him."
31. "He who acts with a constant view to his own advantage will be much murmured against."
32. "The firm, the enduring, the simple, and the modest are near to virtue."
33. "Virtue is more to man than either water or fire. I have seen men die from treading on water and fire, but I have never seen a man die from treading the course of virtue."
34. "To be wronged is nothing unless you continue to remember it."
35. "The superior man is concerned with virtue; the inferior man is concerned with wealth."
36. "The superior man is dignified, but does not wrangle; he is sociable, but not clannish."
37. "The superior man makes the difficulty to be overcome his first interest; success only comes later."
38. "The superior man does not, even for the space of a single meal, act contrary to virtue."
39. "If we don't know life, how can we know death?"
40. "Only the wisest and the stupidest of men never change."

### On Leadership and Government:
41. "The superior man is modest in his speech, but exceeds in his actions."
42. "He who exercises government by means of his virtue may be compared to the north polar star, which keeps its place and all the stars turn towards it."
43. "To lead an uninstructed people to war is to throw them away."
44. "The superior man cannot be known in little matters, but he may be entrusted with great concerns."
45. "He who governs by his excellence makes happy those who are near, and those who are far will come."
46. "A ruler who governs his state by virtue is like the north star, which remains in its place while all the other stars revolve around it."
47. "Good government obtains when those who are near are made happy, and those who are far are attracted."
48. "In a country well governed, poverty is something to be ashamed of. In a country badly governed, wealth is something to be ashamed of."
49. "He who wishes to secure the good of others has already secured his own."
50. "A prince should employ his minister according to the law; conduct himself towards the people with kindness."
51. "He who governs by his excellence makes happy those who are near, and those who are far will come."
52. "The superior man seeks what is right; the inferior one, what is profitable."
53. "The superior man makes the difficulty to be overcome his first interest; success only comes later."
54. "When a country is well governed, poverty and a mean condition are things to be ashamed of. When a country is ill governed, riches and honor are things to be ashamed of."
55. "If a minister makes his own conduct correct, what difficulty will he have in assisting in government? If he cannot rectify himself, what has he to do with rectifying others?"
56. "The superior man is dignified, but does not wrangle; he is sociable, but not clannish."
57. "The superior man understands what is right; the inferior man understands what will sell."
58. "The superior man is firm in the right way, and not merely firm."
59. "The superior man wishes to be slow in his words and earnest in his conduct."
60. "The superior man acts before he speaks, and afterwards speaks according to his actions."

### On Life and Humanity:
61. "Life is really simple, but we insist on making it complicated."
62. "The superior man is satisfied and composed; the mean man is always full of distress."
63. "The more man meditates upon good thoughts, the better will be his world and the world at large."
64. "We take greater pains to persuade others that we are happy than in trying to think so ourselves."
65. "To go beyond is as wrong as to fall short."
66. "When we see persons of worth, we should think of equaling them; when we see persons of a contrary character, we should turn inwards and examine ourselves."
67. "A youth, when at home, should be filial and, abroad, respectful to his elders."
68. "There are three things men find delight in that are advantageous: to be kind, to be wise, and to be sincere."
69. "Men's natures are alike; it is their habits that carry them far apart."
70. "To see what is right and not do it is the want of courage."
71. "The man of wisdom is never in two minds; the man of benevolence never worries; the man of courage is never afraid."
72. "He who conquers himself is the mightiest warrior."
73. "Respect yourself and others will respect you."
74. "It does not matter how slowly you go as long as you do not stop."
75. "To be wronged is nothing unless you continue to remember it."
76. "When it is obvious that the goals cannot be reached, don't adjust the goals, adjust the action steps."
77. "When you have faults, do not fear to abandon them."
78. "He who acts with a constant view to his own advantage will be much murmured against."
79. "When anger rises, think of the consequences."
80. "Choose a job you love, and you will never have to work a day in your life."
81. "The will to win, the desire to succeed, the urge to reach your full potential... these are the keys that will unlock the door to personal excellence."
82. "When you meet someone better than yourself, turn your thoughts to becoming his equal. When you meet someone not as good as you are, look within and examine your own self."
83. "To be wealthy and honored in an unjust society is a disgrace."
84. "Real knowledge is to know the extent of one's ignorance."
85. "Silence is a true friend who never betrays."
86. "Hold faithfulness and sincerity as first principles."
87. "To see what is right and not do it is the want of courage."
88. "In a country well governed, poverty is something to be ashamed of. In a country badly governed, wealth is something to be ashamed of."
89. "If we don't know life, how can we know death?"
90. "Old age, believe me, is a good and pleasant thing. It is true you are gently shouldered off the stage, but then you are given such a comfortable front stall as spectator."

### On Self-Cultivation and Discipline:
91. "The superior man is modest in his speech, but exceeds in his actions."
92. "Do not impose on others what you yourself do not desire."
93. "When we see men of a contrary character, we should turn inwards and examine
